<h3>Architecture</h3>
<p>Pagination is a <strong>Module</strong> that composes the <code>page</code> stage of Collection Operations; it owns only the paging UI and URL/advance wiring, delegating rendering and lifecycle to its neighbours:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>PaginationModule</strong>: resolves the active page + total against the <a href="/resources/pagination/">Custom Pagination</a> resource protocol and exposes the page-state model.</li>
  <li><strong>PaginationBehavior</strong> (<code>page:nav</code>): attaches to the control container, renders the <code>&lt;nav aria-label="pagination"&gt;</code> landmark, projects <code>aria-current="page"</code> onto the active link, and (when <code>withUrlSync</code>) reflects the page to <code>?page=n</code>.</li>
  <li><a href="/intents/windowed-collection/">Windowed Collection</a> renders the visible slice; <a href="/intents/loader/">Loader</a> owns the <code>loadingMore</code> lifecycle at the <code>advance:auto</code> sentinel. <strong>Compose, never merge.</strong></li>
</ul>

<h3>Presentation — two orthogonal axes</h3>
<p><code>pageMode</code> (does advancing <em>replace</em> the slice or <em>grow</em> the list) and <code>advance</code> (is the next slice requested by a <em>click</em> or <em>automatically</em> at the scroll boundary) are independent. <strong>Infinite scroll is not a third mode</strong> — it is <code>append</code> + <code>advance:auto</code>, a derived opt-in carrying the documented infinite-scroll harms (unreachable footer, no stopping point), so it is never the default.</p>
<table>
  <tr><th></th><th><code>advance: manual</code></th><th><code>advance: auto</code></th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>pageMode: paged</code></td><td>Numbered / prev-next — replace the slice on click (jump-to-page, known total)</td><td><em>Undefined</em> — you do not auto-replace a slice on scroll</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>pageMode: append</code></td><td>Load-more button — grow the list on click</td><td>Infinite scroll — grow the list at an IntersectionObserver sentinel</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Accessibility contract (verified)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Controls live in a <code>&lt;nav aria-label="pagination"&gt;</code> navigation landmark; give each landmark a unique label when more than one exists.</li>
  <li>The active page link carries <code>aria-current="page"</code> (WAI-ARIA APG, primary source).</li>
  <li><strong>Open:</strong> focus management and screen-reader announcement <em>after</em> a page change are not yet verified — tracked in <a href="/backlog/059-pagination-focus-announcement/">#059</a>, deliberately unresolved here rather than guessed.</li>
</ul>

<h3>SEO / SSR (load-bearing, not optional)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Each page is a unique, self-referencing canonical <code>?page=n</code>; never canonicalize the sequence to page 1, and never use fragments for page numbers.</li>
  <li>Server-rendered <code>&lt;a href&gt;</code> page links are the SEO-safe default — Googlebot does not fire the user-action JS behind load-more / <code>advance:auto</code>, so an indexable paginated path must exist alongside the interactive UI.</li>
  <li><code>rel=next/prev</code> was deprecated by Google (2019); at most an optional hint, never primary machinery.</li>
  <li>Consequence: <code>urlSync: query-param</code> is <strong>load-bearing</strong> for <code>append</code> modes — without it the footer and back button break.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Cross-layer constraint</h3>
<p>A <a href="/resources/pagination/">resource pagination protocol</a> choice binds what UX is expressible: <strong>jump-to-page and the <code>rangeLabel</code></strong> (<code>"showing 21–40 of 500"</code>) need a known total, so they pair <strong>only</strong> with an offset/page protocol. A cursor protocol has no total and structurally forces prev-next or load-more with <code>rangeLabel</code> off. This constraint is inherited from the resource layer, not re-modeled here.</p>

<h3>HTML Usage</h3>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!-- Numbered pagination (paged + manual), SEO-safe server-rendered links --&gt;
&lt;nav page:nav aria-label="pagination" data-url-sync="query-param"&gt;
  &lt;a href="?page=1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;a href="?page=2" aria-current="page"&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;a href="?page=3"&gt;3&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;a href="?page=3"&gt;Next&lt;/a&gt;&lt;!-- no rel=next/prev: deprecated, never primary machinery --&gt;
&lt;/nav&gt;

&lt;!-- Infinite scroll (append + auto): a sentinel the IntersectionObserver watches --&gt;
&lt;ul windowed-collection&gt;&lt;!-- rendered slice --&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;div page:nav data-page-mode="append" data-advance="auto" aria-hidden="true"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Interface (contracts only)</h3>
<p>Web Everything defines the contract; concrete strategy implementations (a URL-state provider, an alternate advance trigger) live in <strong>Frontier UI</strong> and register against these seams without changing the contract.</p>
<pre><code class="language-typescript">type PageMode = 'paged' | 'append';
type Advance  = 'manual' | 'auto';
type UrlSync  = 'none' | 'query-param';
type RangeLabel = 'none' | 'range';

interface PageState {
  pageIndex: number;          // zero-based active page
  pageSize: number;           // items per slice (selector defaults pending #060)
  pageCount?: number;         // absent under a cursor protocol (no total)
  total?: number;             // absent under a cursor protocol
}

interface PaginationContract {
  mode: PageMode;
  advance: Advance;           // default 'manual'; append + auto = infinite scroll
  urlSync: UrlSync;           // 'query-param' writes a self-canonical ?page=n
  rangeLabel: RangeLabel;     // 'range' requires a total -> offset/page protocol only
  // Observable events: 'pagechange' (the page stage of the intent's pipeline events).
}</code></pre>

<h3>Status &amp; scope</h3>
<p><code>status: draft</code> — the contract, a11y/SEO/URL-state design, and a fixture-driven
<a href="/demos/pagination-demo.html">conformance demo</a> ship here; concrete strategy
implementations are deferred to Frontier UI. The companion <code>sortDirection → aria-sort</code>
projection and the filter/sort/group rendering home belong to a separate grid/data-table block,
tracked independently.</p>
